00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:23.800
worked my week in hand and come back.

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:25.800
I come back.

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:27.800
I didn't

00:11:27.800 --> 00:11:29.800
like Smiths. It was

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:31.800
so different to our factory.

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:33.800
They were very, very

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.800
strict. You had to put your hand up to

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:37.800
go to the toilet and you wasn't allowed to talk

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:39.800
to the girl next to you,

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:41.800
which our factory was totally different to that.

00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:45.800
So at Danx, do you think they were good

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:47.800
employers? Very good.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:49.800
Yeah.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.800
So, you know,

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:53.800
you started talking about what you did

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:55.800
in the factory. Did your work

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:57.800
change over the years?

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:59.800
You know, from when you began?

00:11:59.800 --> 00:12:01.800
No, no,

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:03.800
we were always working on jackets and

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:05.800
you know, it's so

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:07.800
funny because

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:09.800
they'd start on the line by

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:11.800
you and by the time they got down

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:13.800
to the bottom of the line,

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:15.800
there was two jackets missing

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:17.800
and nobody knew where

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:19.800
they went, didn't they?

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:21.800
Or they were taking parts so

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:23.800
when they'd go home they'd sew them and

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:25.800
make them up, make a jacket

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:27.800
up when they get home, you know?

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:29.800
But that went on, I mean,

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:31.800
that went on, people knew. And

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:33.800
cotton reels,

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:35.800
you were allowed to take cotton reels home.

00:12:35.800 --> 00:12:37.800
You could have the cotton reels,

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:39.800
you know, they never stopped you.

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:41.800
I mean, nobody done a lot

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:43.800
of pinching, but

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:45.800
you could have a reel of white cotton

00:12:45.800 --> 00:12:47.800
if you wanted it, like you knew

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:49.800
they didn't stop you doing that.

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:51.800
You know?

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:53.800
I think I got one reels

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:55.800
here from the factory.

00:12:55.800 --> 00:12:57.800
But, you know,

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.800
it wasn't, well,

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.800
as I said, they were pretty lenient

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:03.800
with us. And who had a canteen

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:05.800
where you had food?

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:07.800
You go and have food.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.800
Do you want to ask that?

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:11.800
Here we go then.

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:13.800
I was going to ask you, I know

00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:15.800
I asked you what was it

00:13:15.800 --> 00:13:17.800
like when you first worked, but what was it

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:19.800
like, the sights and the smells

00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:21.800
of the place? Can you describe the factory

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:23.800
to me? Yeah.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:25.800
Erm, we had

00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:27.800
chalk.

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:29.800
We used to chalk,

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:31.800
you had to mark your

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:33.800
garment. So the chalk

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:35.800
and everything, the smell

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:37.800
of all the cottons and that,

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:39.800
because all the alleyways around

00:13:39.800 --> 00:13:41.800
the lines were all like

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:43.800
fluff. So you had a lot

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:45.800
of fluff with the pieces

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:47.800
of material.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:49.800
They had a big cutting room they did

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:51.800
and that cutting room,

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:53.800
they'd done layers and layers of material

00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:55.800
and they had like

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:57.800
band knives. They were very

00:13:57.800 --> 00:13:59.800
long knives and

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:01.800
like you had big things like that

00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:03.800
that you pushed through the band knife

00:14:03.800 --> 00:14:05.800
and they'd cut hundreds of patterns

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:07.800
out in one go.

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:09.800
Well before they came on the line

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:11.800
and that was called the cutting

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:13.800
room. Well there was about

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:15.800
12 people working in there.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:17.800
And erm

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:19.800
before it came out on

00:14:19.800 --> 00:14:21.800
the floor. But it did smell

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:23.800
like erm, I

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:25.800
can't explain, like

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:27.800
fluffy material. I mean

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:29.800
I expect we had, I don't know,

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:31.800
the fluff was everywhere

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:33.800
because you had it all on your

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:35.800
clothes and your hair.

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:37.800
Especially on the duffel coats

00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:39.800
because they were

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:41.800
thick material.

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:43.800
And erm.

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:45.800
Was it a good smell? Yeah.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:47.800
Yeah. You were used to

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:49.800
it. You'd go in in the morning

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:51.800
and well it was just

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:53.800
you got used to it.

00:14:53.800 --> 00:14:55.800
Did you wear any protection

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:57.800
on your? No.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:14:59.800
Do you think you should have?

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:01.800
I think we should have

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:03.800
especially working on that

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:05.800
fluffy stuff like in there.

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:07.800
When you press your button on your buttonhole

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:09.800
erm

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:11.800
I mean I was going round in like

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:13.800
that doing the buttonhole

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:15.800
where the fluff was coming up

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:17.800
onto your face and

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:19.800
but they never

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:21.800
thought of things like that in them days

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:23.800
did they? No they didn't.

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:25.800
Because we had silks

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:27.800
for the lining of the jacket. You had

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:29.800
silk and they were all

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:31.800
that was all erm

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:33.800
that was all fluffy and threading.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:35.800
All the threads was all on the floor

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:37.800
from the cut-ins

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:39.800
and that.

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:41.800
And trousers you didn't think

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:43.800
that the duffel coats

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:45.800
was the worst.

00:15:45.800 --> 00:15:47.800
You know.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:49.800
Was the condition of the factory, did it feel clean?

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:51.800
Oh yeah they had

00:15:51.800 --> 00:15:53.800
cleaners.

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:55.800
They had cleaners going round in

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:57.800
when you left work

00:15:57.800 --> 00:15:59.800
the cleaners would come in and sweep

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:01.800
they'd sweep all the fluff.

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:03.800
You wouldn't have yesterday's

00:16:03.800 --> 00:16:05.800
bits and bobs all on the floor

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:07.800
that would be gone.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:09.800
And they had

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:11.800
a cleaner in the toilet.

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:13.800
The toilet was clean.

00:16:13.800 --> 00:16:15.800
But erm, one day

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:17.800
one girl, somebody threw a cotton

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:19.800
reel at her and she had locked

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:21.800
her jaw. She threw it across

00:16:21.800 --> 00:16:23.800
the factory

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:25.800
onto the other line and she had

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:27.800
locked jaw. But erm

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:29.800
you would fool about, you could fool about

00:16:29.800 --> 00:16:31.800
they didn't stop

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:33.800
you like in it.

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:35.800
And they'd shout over and you know

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:37.800
and you had like Silla Black

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:39.800
playing over on the radio.

00:16:39.800 --> 00:16:41.800
And it was allowed and they'd all be

00:16:41.800 --> 00:16:43.800
singing to Silla Black.

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:45.800
Erm.

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:47.800
Do you remember what the programmes were? You know.

00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:49.800
And do you remember what the songs were?

00:16:49.800 --> 00:16:51.800
Yeah, it was erm

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:53.800
You're My World

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:55.800
with Silla Black. It was all

00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:57.800
fifties music.

00:16:57.800 --> 00:16:59.800
And it was records

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:01.800
because they had a record

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:03.800
machine up the office.

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:05.800
And they used to play all the records.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:07.800
Or you'd bring your own records in and they'd

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:09.800
play them for you. You could

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:11.800
do that.

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:13.800
But you went in relays

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:15.800
to the canteen.

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:17.800
Like say

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:19.800
past twelve you a line would go.

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:21.800
And then one o'clock another line would go.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:23.800
So, you know.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:25.800
But you could have hot meal.

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:27.800
Or you could have sandwiches

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:29.800
and tea and that.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:31.800
And they had a boiler house.

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:33.800
Well the boiler house used to

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:35.800
make all the heating you know.

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:37.800
Because my father, there was a man

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:39.800
working in the boiler house.

00:17:39.800 --> 00:17:41.800
From over the valley.

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:43.800
But erm, you didn't

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:45.800
take any notice of the smell.

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:47.800
I think Denix smelled

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:49.800
Denix like it was a factory.

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:51.800
Yeah.

00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:53.800
You'd accept it that.

00:17:53.800 --> 00:17:55.800
And if he was getting married they'd tie

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:57.800
you to the machine with all things on it.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:59.800
If he was getting married

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:01.800
they'd done that to me and I was nearly

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:03.800
dying. My mother and father was there.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:05.800
But erm

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:07.800
it was the best place.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:09.800
We all say now we've

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:11.800
nowhere in our seventies we wish it was

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:13.800
we were still going.

00:18:13.800 --> 00:18:15.800
Because we meet up all the girls

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:17.800
in Tudiga. We see them.

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:19.800
They'd go out yeah like a

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:21.800
they're like sisters they are.

00:18:21.800 --> 00:18:23.800
Because we had that bond you know.

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:25.800
Like erm, we went

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:27.800
in the toilet one day and this girl

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:29.800
pierced my ears with a needle

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:31.800
and soap.

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:33.800
But erm, you know

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:35.800
I was only about seventeen and I was

00:18:35.800 --> 00:18:37.800
bleeding on my ear.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:39.800
But no it was a good

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:41.800
place to work.

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:43.800
The companionship was there.

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:45.800
Because this one girl

00:18:45.800 --> 00:18:47.800
was from Rhymney was going to beat

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:49.800
my friend up in it. And then

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:51.800
there was about ten waiting for her outside.

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:53.800
They wouldn't have touched her like

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:55.800
you know they were that

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:57.800
close that you

00:18:57.800 --> 00:18:59.800
they were ganged up with her you know they

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:01.800
wouldn't have her.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:03.800
So did you go there?

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:05.800
You know you said your

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:07.800
your mum was there yeah?

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:09.800
Your dad was there. Did you go there

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:11.800
with girls from school?

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:13.800
Yeah, yeah.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:15.800
And girls who lived around the factory

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:17.800
in the streets.

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:19.800
Because once the Oota would go

00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:21.800
they'd come from all the streets around

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:23.800
you know.

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:25.800
And they had a little

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:27.800
two shops, two little shops at the bottom

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.800
of the road. And that's where

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:31.800
you'd get your sweets or whatever for dinner.

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:33.800
And then the Oota would go

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:35.800
and you'd be going walking back.

00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:37.800
But it was about

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:39.800
300 people there.

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:41.800
Were you mainly

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:43.800
women or women and men?

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:45.800
Women and men but the

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:47.800
men were more or less in the cutting room.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:51.800
And they had supervisor men

00:19:51.800 --> 00:19:53.800
on the presses.

00:19:53.800 --> 00:19:55.800
Because we had automatic big

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:57.800
presses to press the

00:19:57.800 --> 00:19:59.800
jackets and that. And they

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:01.800
were overseeing

00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.800
the presses.

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:05.800
The men.

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:07.800
So how many women say to men?

00:20:07.800 --> 00:20:09.800
Do you think?

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:11.800
I would say there would only be about

00:20:11.800 --> 00:20:13.800
40 men.

00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:15.800
And all the rest was women.

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:17.800
So hundreds of women?

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:19.800
Oh yeah, yeah.

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:21.800
Did Tridiga women go and work

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:23.800
anywhere else?

00:20:23.800 --> 00:20:25.800
Yeah, some went to

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:27.800
the bra factory in

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:29.800
Ebbw Vale, Burleys.

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:31.800
And a lot went

00:20:31.800 --> 00:20:33.800
to the Smiths.

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:35.800
So that sewing factory in Rhymney.

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:37.800
Some didn't come to Denix,

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:39.800
they just went to Smiths.

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:41.800
You know.

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:43.800
Or when that day I went looking for a job

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:45.800
I went over Triang.

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:47.800
In Merthyr. That was a

00:20:47.800 --> 00:20:49.800
Triang Toys. That was a

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:51.800
big factory over there.

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:53.800
But I didn't get a job over there.

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:57.800
So could you walk?

00:20:57.800 --> 00:20:59.800
You could walk to work then? Yeah.

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:01.800
I could see the factory.

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:03.800
The factory was like those houses

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:05.800
over there. It was only the distance of

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:07.800
looking at the factory. I was looking

00:21:07.800 --> 00:21:09.800
at it every day. And was that

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:11.800
okay? Yeah.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:13.800
Yeah. That's why I wanted a brick

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:15.800
when it broke.

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:17.800
Well it was lovely, it was lovely.

00:21:17.800 --> 00:21:19.800
But it was turned into

00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:21.800
I mean it shut for

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.800
a long time. Years.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:25.800
And then this other firm

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:27.800
took over and they were making plastic

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:29.800
bowls.

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:31.800
And they took it over, the LCR did.

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:33.800
But

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:35.800
as I said I got married

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:37.800
and I didn't go, you know, I never went

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:39.800
back there. But my mother and

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:41.800
father stayed there.

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:43.800
They worked until it closed.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:45.800
Okay. I'll get to

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:47.800
that in a bit.

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:49.800
Can you just, we'll go back to

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:51.800
when they did children's clothes,

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:53.800
where were those clothes?

00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:55.800
Do you know who, where

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:57.800
they went? They went to London.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:21:59.800
Burton on Trent.

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:01.800
Because

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:03.800
my father was driving the van

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:05.800
and when we were little, we used to go

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:07.800
in the van with him and he'd take us to

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:09.800
Burton on Trent or we'd stay in London

